##Beijing domestic workers: Unable to return to Beijing, no isolation, no work to do

Southreviews

Functional presentation, the power of calm

The following article is from the new weekly, by Zhao Jingyi

"New weekly" was founded on August 18,1996, by the Southern Publishing Media Co. , Ltd. , director, sponsored, to "China's most cutting-edge lifestyle weekly" as the positioning, launched a series of highly influential special reports, it is one of the most representative and influential magazines in China's periodical market, and enjoys the reputation of "topic source" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Under the epidemic, many unseen scenes become common, and once simple things have become very difficult.

The sudden outbreak of the epidemic, so that domestic workers work rhythm in the "upper" and "lower" constantly switch between. In the vast Beijing city, they stayed in their rented rooms, waiting for the sun to shine after the outbreak.

If you leave one day late, Miss Chen may not be able to return to Beijing.

She is a domestic hourly worker, engaged in ten years, Langzhong people in Sichuan. In Beijing, she lives in Feijia village, near Wangjing, just outside the fifth ring road. On Feb. 3, she planned to return to Beijing from her hometown.

She had heard the news from Beijing before -- as the outbreak grew, the village was once off limits to tenants and then quarantined for a week. The village is home to hundreds of villagers and tens of thousands of outsiders.

To get to Langzhong station, she had to take the coach, and when she stopped, she bought two catties of pork off the side of the road. She took with her ten catties of sharp peas and rape. "I'm afraid I won't be allowed to go out and I won't be able to buy food in the village. "

In February, those remote villages were alerted to the outbreak. In previous years, Ms. Chen would bring along Zhang Fei beef, a Langzhong specialty, to give to her employers. But now, all the shops in town are closed.

Into the city, pedestrians are few, she dare not wander. On the bullet train for more than ten hours, little Chen did not drink a mouthful of water, because she did not dare to take off her mask.

The next day, she heard her family say, "the village closed, the road closed, the bus stopped. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At first, no one realized what was coming next. Photography / Priming

The road back to Beijing

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
If you want to enter the village, you must ask the landlord to pick you up. In the cold winter, Miss Chen waited for an hour and finally got home.

Outside the Fifth Ring Road in Beijing, there are many places like Feijia village. These villages, scattered on the outskirts of the city, are now a refuge for migrant workers: relatively cheap rents and easy access to the city for work.

Ms. Chen moved here in 2017 to live with her daughter, who returned to Chengdu last year to work and is all alone in her 1,600-yuan-a-month apartment.

"I want to work for a few more years and the rent will be just fine. "

According to the plan, after a week of isolation, Miss Chen will be able to get a pass. On the first day of the Lunar New Year, the village of Feijia is in a state of strong closure. Tenants staying in Beijing need to apply for a certificate. There used to be several entrances to the village, but now only one is left.

At first, it took a long time to get a license. At 4 o'clock in the afternoon, the manager said, "No more. ". The tenants are not satisfied, to the online post complaints, later, the village began to overnight card.

At one point, the village did not allow tenants from eight provinces, including Hubei, Anhui and Henan, to return to the village. But the dispute became so contentious that residents from these provinces were placed in isolation for two weeks, and those from other provinces for a week.

A checkpoint patrols in front of the village of Fei Jia. Photo / Grain Introduction

The week of isolation was too boring for Miss Chen and she had to sleep in it.

She had a busy schedule, working four jobs a day:

From 6:30 am, I work 3 hours cleaning in a kindergarten

At 10 a.m. , go to an employer's house to clean and cook lunch

After lunch, stay at another employer's home for 4 hours, do Housework, Cook Dinner, and then return to the kindergarten to wash dishes for 1 hour;

6:30 p.m. , another two hours cleaning at a pharmaceutical company.

These jobs enable her to earn more than 10,000 yuan a month. But now, a sudden outbreak has broken all that.

On the second day of the New Year, Miss Chen received a phone call from her employer, saying that she would not ask for her help after years.

This is an ordinary family, living 60 square meters of two-bedroom. The mother of the female employer, who had cancer and was unable to take care of her primary-school grandchild, hired hourly workers.

Miss Chen has been working in this family for more than two years, doing housework and cooking dinner, and getting on well with each other. When she first arrived, she told her female employer that the work would not take four hours. It was very considerate of her to take an hour's nap.

"She said to me, I'm really sorry, but now that the tourism industry is dead and she has no job herself, she plans to take her children home to primary school and graduate. I said it's okay, I understand, people are helpless, " Ms. Chen said.

Private kindergartens are temporarily closed because of the outbreak. There are only two jobs left for Miss Chen. The pharmaceutical company told her she would be paid during the quarantine.

Another family employed Miss Chen for 10 years. She cooks lunch at the House and eats with her employer's family. At first it was a family of four, two children grew up, only the two employers, one of them business, the other called Little Miss Chen come over to eat.

The family was not surprised that the people back to Beijing need to quarantine this matter, they told Xiaochen Jie: "You see can secretly run out, and talk to people? "

Back in Feijia village, Miss Chen shows her pass to the staff. Photography / Priming

After a week of isolation, Miss Chen went to work for a few days. At this time, the village issued a new regulation, from the day of the village, all tenants have to be isolated for two weeks.

Just got the key card, and it's gone.

Between the two of you

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In early February, Umewaka, the head of Beijing's Hongyan Social Work Service Center, received a call from Li Ping, a mother in law who had been working for 10 days, subcontractors (such as Yuesao, Yuesao, Nannies and other domestic workers usually work for only one employer, finding a new one is called "Shanghu" and leaving one is called "Xiahu") and the agency refuses to pay her. She was supposed to get $3,600 back at the agreed price.

For more than 20 days, Umewaka has been working at his home in Tianjin. She's busier than usual. She's getting a lot of calls for help. Beijing Hongyan Social Work Service Center is a public welfare organization dedicated to domestic workers, who call it "home of Hongyan" .

There are an estimated 35m domestic workers in China, a hidden and important contributor to urbanisation.

The epidemic has made disputes that have existed in the past sharp and ambiguous. In twenty-eight, Li Ping went to work for a mother who had just given birth to a second child.

"She agreed with the agency that she would pay 14,800 yuan a month, and the agency would take 4,000 yuan. The employer would pay extra for the three days of Spring Festival. In the end, Li Ping received only overtime pay, " UMEWAKA said.

Li Ping only worked for ten days because she thought her employer was too strict. With 10 years of experience as a matchmaker, she feels a bit aggrieved, such as giving her baby to her mother temporarily while she cooks for her baby, but the other party is critical: "The last time I invited a matchmaker, I didn't even have to touch the baby. "

Li Ping had asked to resign twice, and her employer had retained her until the third time, when she finally agreed. The agency's attitude is: "You ruined my list, broke the contract, do not want to take ten days of money. "

Learning of the situation, Umewaka called the agency. "It is not professional for her to abandon her employer during an outbreak and just leave, whether someone takes over or not, " she said

The two sides have spoken several times. In the past, Umewaka has never taken the initiative to negotiate directly. Instead, he has tried to get domestic workers to "understand the situation" and learn to negotiate and defend their rights. But Li Ping was not used to dealing with people with strong personalities, and the agency blocked her wechat account. When she called, she was scolded again.

Little Miss Chen's bike. On weekdays, she worked four jobs a day. 6:30 a.m. , 8:30 p.m. Six months ago, the village confiscated her electric bike and replaced it with a bicycle to get to work. When the epidemic came, Miss Chen lost half her job. But in fact, she's one of the lucky tens of millions. Photography / Zhao Jingyi

Both sides have their own theories about Li Ping's departure.

The agency believes that Li Ping was just trying to earn overtime pay for the Spring Festival, and that he left because he had a new job. During the dispute, the intermediary contacted Li Ping on Wechat and asked her to open a video call, but Li Ping did not answer, and suspected that she had been registered.

UMEWAKA believes Li Ping because of the "very quiet and obviously unemployed" environment in which the two sides had spoken several times.

"She was misunderstood because while working in her employer's home, her last client asked her about child care on Wechat. When she heard the voice, the current employer was not satisfied and thought she was looking for a new job, " UMEWAKA said.

Misunderstandings that used to be able to communicate and explain have become difficult to explain at this particular time. Both Li Ping and the agency were to blame, Umewaka said, for not predicting the impact of the outbreak. The agent should talk to Li Ping and convince her to stay in the house.

"The agency said it was difficult to find someone to take over, and the employer didn't trust the new comer to return to Beijing without quarantine. The agency blamed the loss on the sister. "

Not having a job is the most common impact of the outbreak on the domestic sector than a work dispute. Some can not find new jobs, some are quarantined by their employers but can not find a place to do so. These difficulties encountered by domestic workers are a microcosm of the difficulties in returning to work in the near future.

On Feb. 8, when Umewaka finally settled Li Ping's case, the agency paid Li Ping 2,000 yuan, with each side assuming responsibility.

Finding a job is becoming more and more difficult for domestic workers

Stranded at home

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 18, Chen Yulu left for his hometown of Datong.

The reason for going home was that she felt that her previous employer was too harsh, "watching the housekeeper like a servant. At home, she didn't dare to speak. ".

Over the past two years, the employer often travel, during which she gave a long vacation, but will be deducted from her monthly salary.

"They're leaving the next day, and I told you the night before, they don't need to come for a few days, " Chen Yulu said, adding several times that he wanted to be told ahead of time that he was going home to buy a ticket. Several Times, she bought standing tickets.

Years ago, Chen Yulu told his employer 10 days in advance that he was "not coming back" . The other person was very angry and thought she should have made it clear two months in advance.

"Who could have foreseen this early? " She was a little aggrieved. "I said, you didn't even ask her to travel. " The host was annoyed: "Why should I ask you to travel? I pay you to travel whenever I want. "

A few days after returning home, Chen Yulu received a call from her son asking her to buy a mask. Chen Yulu's 22 year old son teaches musical instruments in Tianjin. When he heard about the local confirmed cases, masks were hard to come by.

Putting down his son's phone, Chen Yulu ran to the pharmacy and bought 60 surgical masks. It's her last chance to buy a mask.

It wasn't until twenty-eight that Chen Yulu discovered that the epidemic was really about him. Home Economics Company Group, the manager sent a message: The end of the year, do not hurry back, dormitory closed. "He said if we go back, we'll be quarantined for 14 days, but we don't have a place to live, so where are we quarantined? "

Chen Yulu didn't have a good new year. She stayed at home, worried that she wouldn't get a job. "I was helpless when I heard this. Life is stressful because you only get one day's pay for one day's work. "

Three years ago, Chen Yulu moved to Beijing as a stay at home wife. According to her experience, the peak period for job hunting is after the Spring Festival. "normally, I go back to Beijing on the sixth day of the Lunar New Year. After the Lantern Festival, a large number of people go back to Beijing, and domestic workers' dormitories are crowded, so it's very stressful to find work. "

She described the domestic service company to find work like a talent show, the employer came, the arrangement of three people to go, one by one to see, "is a conversation, the employer does not feel good to change to the next, until until satisfaction. ".

The supply of domestic workers exceeds the supply in case of epidemic

These agencies, big and small, typically charge domestic workers 10 to 30 percent of the monthly fee. Agencies can provide paid daily accommodation for domestic workers to help them get through the gap.

Most live-in Nannies find an employer through an agency. But the outbreak has shut down dormitories and put domestic workers in limbo.

Chen Yulu said the training institute where his son worked had not been able to tell the time of day. During this time, the son also lost income.

Li Mengyu, who lives in Pingliang, Gansu Province, could not get to Xi'an by train because of the road closures.

She has not discussed with her employer when she will return to work, or whether she will need to be quarantined for two weeks after returning to Beijing. Her job is to take care of a two-year-old, but because of the epidemic, the employer also stayed at home to work, "I have to say hello to go, ask bad not to go. ".

For more than a month, her village was sealed off from visiting her single mother in another village. In his spare time, Li Mengyu reads the books he brings home from Beijing and writes. However, she was ridiculed by fellow villagers, "said I become a city people, look down on them" "laugh at me want to be a writer" ..

Ms. Li said she was stifled by rural traditions and conservatism because of the "grounding" brought about by the epidemic.

Long road back to Beijing, I do not know how long to wait.

There's no way to isolate it

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When live-in Nannies return to Beijing, employers typically require them to be isolated for a while. Some families will provide a place to live, Umewaka said, but many more will not and will need a nanny to figure it out for themselves.

At the Swan Goose home, there was a woman called Miss Tan. A native of Sichuan Province, she left home for Beijing after a bad relationship with her husband in Guangdong.

Last year, she went back to Huizhou to attend her daughter's wedding and gave her a "big red envelope" . The money she could make raising a baby in Beijing gave Tan confidence, but the children never came to see her.

During her 10 years in Beijing, Miss Tan had no fixed residence. She lives with her employer and moves from family to family. In her spare time, the agency's dorms were her home.

UMEWAKA has known sister Tam for a long time. "She graduated from a technical secondary school and has a good education. Once in a cooking class, she accidentally stepped on a pot of boiling water and disfigured her face. She has had a rough life, but she has lived a very full life. "

Before she returned to Beijing, Umewaka tried to get her a place to live, but failed. "I asked some friends if they had a place to stay. Miss Tan also asked Miss Chen, but then Miss Chen's niece moved in... "

On the seventh day of the New Year, Miss Tan moved into her hometown. Knowing she was back, her employer sent her a mask and promised to pay her during the quarantine.

That day, Umewaka received counseling from another parenting sister.

She said her employer urged her to return to work and offered her a house to be quarantined for five days. Only noodles and instant noodles remained in the house, and she had to do the rest herself. The mother-in-law thought the five days of isolation should be paid, but the employer consulted the agency and said no payment was required.

"I told her there was no clear law on the matter. "When you return from a 12-hour drive from Linyi in Shandong Province and risk cross-infection on the way back, you are quarantined for five days and the employer is supposed to pay the cost, but further negotiations are needed. "

The next night, the mother-in-law sent Umewaka a message on Wechat: "I feel locked in my heart. I want to go home. "

Going back to work in the city is a long way off

Fewer jobs

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 22, after investigating 90 domestic workers, Hongyan home released a report on the epidemic situation of domestic workers. The results of the survey show that 40 per cent of people affected by the epidemic have been unable to work for a considerable period of time and 20 per cent have lost their jobs.

For a long time, little Chen could only work two jobs. On February 13, when the quarantine period ended, she was able to enter and leave the village. At noon, after leaving her employer's house, she went straight to the pharmaceutical company.

These days, the company to work very few people, do a lot less difficult to clean. The company had a full-time cleaning staff, and one and little Miss Chen, only two hours a day. They didn't come back. They're stuck back home.

Miss Chen calculated a sum of money: "The company said to me, let me first all inclusive, the other two people's wages are calculated to me. ". Until they come back, my income isn't much different than it used to be. But that private kindergarten is so new, it could go out of business. We still have to find a way to fill these holes."

Miss Chen goes home before 4 o'clock every afternoon. In that small apartment, she cooked hot pot, baked potato cakes, pickled cabbage noodles, and made a small video posted on the Internet.

UMEWAKA has always found little Miss Chen optimistic, "she likes to drink red wine. So hard, do not force a living, how to support. ".

Another day labourer Umewaka knew, who lived in the village of Feijia, spent the year alone. The village is closed, and her husband and son, both in Beijing, can not get through. She's out of the village now, but she spends more time at home lying down because there's nothing to do.

"unlike Miss Chen, she has a very tight schedule and a good relationship with her employer. She's a loose cannon, not very organized. Her employers are fluid. They don't go to the same place every day. There is work to do, not also anxious, often see work on the door, there is a speculative, take the opportunity to find more money."

"She often takes on dubious jobs, often without a contract. Over the years, I've gone with her several times to her employer's house to ask for money. "

Past employers told her not to go recently, because she knew that many home "string" , for fear of cross-infection. In fact, she had only one job at the time, feeding the cat, because her employer was away in the south for the New Year.

"I told you you'd get nothing, " UMEWAKA warned by phone. "She was cool about it. She said the whole country was like this. She could lie down for days. What can you do? "

In the days of migrant workers in Beijing, domestic workers would gather at the Beijing Hongyan Social Work Service Center in their spare time to rehearse their programs together. Photograph by Yang Chang

The Group of domestic workers is actually quite optimistic, Umewaka says.

She remembers visiting little Chen in December 2017, when she was living with her sister and niece in Dongxindian village. The small house had no electric heater and was very cold, during which time many of the village's out-of-town tenants moved out in a hurry.

During the conversation, the village again suddenly power failure, as if nothing happened, little sister Chen Lit a candle, continue to talk about the matter happily.

"The sense of disorder, the constant need to be prepared for an accident, is a normal part of life for them. "

"They have developed the ability to be ready for the uncertainty of life. "
